STRIPE RUST, BARLEY - AUSTRALIA (VICTORIA & NSW)
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: Tue, 09 Nov 1999 10:45:08 +1100
From: Lizz K <ekopecny@mail.usyd.edu.au>
Source: Stripe Rust In Victoria [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/rural/news/stories/s64781.htm>

Stripe rust has been confirmed in Victorian barley trials, for the first
time. The disease has been detected in the barley variety Skiff before in
New South Wales, and also in barley grass in Victoria for years.
David Moody, from the Grains Research and Development Corporation, says the
finding may spell the end of the Skiff cultivar. He said that rust has
been found on barley grass in Victoria for a number of years, but
significant levels of the disease had not been seen on barley before. It
probably means growers should avoid growing the most susceptible varieties.
Fortunately only a fairly limited number of cultivars are quite
susceptible. Moody said that most of our cultivars have quite good levels
of resistance to the fungus.
--
Elizabeth Kopecny
Project Officer
Department of Pharmacy (A15) tel: 61-2-9351-3647
University of Sydney fax: 61-2-9351-4391
